<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-20"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-20')">20</a>. Moving this to the Doubt section, because I doubt the absolute fuck out of this hypothesis. In fact, I know it's bullshit because eastern philosophy doesn't really have the concept of a Law of Names, so my father couldn't possibly know about it or incorporate it into his plan. <em>-Hx</em></div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-21"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-21')">21</a>. Nice try, but still bullshit. Pihü 피휘 or the &quot;evasion of true name&quot; (Thanks for the condescending translation, by the way; I <em>do</em> speak Korean), arises from matters of decorum. For example, my father's true name was Woo-chi, but he was called by his art name &quot;Woo-sa (Featherman)&quot; instead, because it was rude to call one's true name in days of old. There's no magical reason. <em>-Hx</em></div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-22"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-22')">22</a>. We can't say for certain. We all know that Robert Bumaro roamed Ancient China. Your father could easily have heard of Hermes Trismegistus from him, or any other explorer that ventured to the Orient. <em>-M.</em></div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-23"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-23')">23</a>. If your hypothesis is right, why didn't my mother lose her powers entirely? If he had really taken on the Name of a demon fox, why would his last act have been sealing her within Peach Blossom Land? It wouldn't, because that makes no sense. <em>-Hx</em></div>
